description.text: For the latest, greatest version, be sure to check out the Eulidit Slant Wallet II with even easier access to cards! (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1229532/). Show off your maker interests by always carrying this functional hard wallet in your pocket. This specially designed wallet holds bills, cards, and coins conveniently together under a sliding lid of your choosing, giving it a unique, personal touch. Standard-sized (U.S.) credit cards, bus passes, and photo ID may be used for the lid.

• You print it. If you often experience curling problems, this print will surely curl due to its large, flat first layers. I recommend printing using a raft with no margin. The wallet prints near the edges of some small beds, so there is not much room to spare.
  • You lid it! Pick your favorite card to use as a lid. Photo ID is great for quick reference. Slide it in the top.
  • Put other cards inside! Put the long side in first and it will easily drop in to place.
  • Load it with whatever you'd like!
    • To remove cards easily, tip to one side and push your finger through a hole in the bottom. (Don't worry, holes are smaller than an American dime.)

title: Prusa i3 MK2S E3D volcano mod

description.text:
Work in progress and untested as of yet.

I want to use a Volcano hotend on my MK2S, but to my surprise, no one seems to have made a mod for this yet. Only for the MK2 (different pinda probe). So I tried my self.

The MK2 volcano extruder cover and fan nozzle are made by dshamiel, I changed nothing, I just uploaded them here for your convenience. The extruder body, which holds the PINDA probe, is a remix of the MK2S original, I basically just "stretched" the pinda holder so it gets lower. Its not ideal, as the screws that clamp the probe are probably further apart than the probe is long, and I couldnt see a way easily extend the grooving properly, but I think it will be good enough until someone makes something better.

description.text:
This mount has room for two pins, that will charge the nexus when you put it in the mount. You will need:

  • An usb cable
  • A small peace of conductive metal, like a nail or similar. Preferably cobber. Iron will do.
  • Sodering equipment
  • Wire cutters

Proceed by cutting the peaces of metal in two bites, one just a tiny bit longer than the other. about 5-7mm in length. they should just stick out a mm or two out of the mount. Make sure they can move freely through the holes. this way they can automatically adjust there height so both connects to the tablet.
Use wire cutters to cut the usb cable. find the + (red) and the - (black) wire and solder them in one end of each of the pins.
insert the pins into the mount from the bottom, along with the cable and fasten the lid with the screw. The + pin goes to the hole furthest near the edge and the screw hole, and the - pin goes to the other hole.
If the pins arn't connecting, you can use a hot pin to move the holes a bit.
If the print is too wide for your tablet, you can use some tabe to thicken one side of the mount, and thereby make the tablet slot smaller.

Enjoy!

#########################################################################
Update 16.09.2017 - (regarding the balancing rod)
#########################################################################

I was looking for a better solution for the balancing rod, it seemed that a simple threaded m4 rod wasn't quite doing the job.

After reading a bit about magnetic balancers it seems that the "lesser" friction of such devices might cause a harder time to actually balance your props.

Here is what I did:

I went to our local hardware store and bought a hardened 4mm rod, I then ground and sharpened each end, and made them spikey. (Updated pictures will follow)

I then realized that the rod itself started to get a magnetic polarization, I then figured out the "middle" position and marked it.

The way of balancing my props looks like this:

Attach the prop to the rod in a way such that the prop is horizontally aligned to the polarization of the rod, then try to balance.

Due to the sensitivity of the system, sometimes I will have to rotate the propeller a couple of degree (2° ~ 5°) to check the horizontal alignment.

Balance the prop if necessary.

title: Print a 3D Map - Draw on top of it

description.text:
This is a 3D Map created from openstreetmaps data on which i have drawn roads, rivers and elevation lines using a pen holder instead of my 3D printer head. (like a 3D plotter).

The most up-to-date detail step-by-step operation is described here: https://sites.google.com/view/3dplotting

Step 0: Print a Pen Holder toolhead.

My simplistic design ( for Creality CR-10) is here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2... There is a lot of room for improvements. If you don’t want to start from scratch, my Fusion360 project is here: http://a360.co/2x2ajtx

Step 1: Gathering topographical data

First, you need to install Maperitive: http://maperitive.net/ . This is a free software that can apparently run on Windows, Mac and Linux (using Mono). I have tested it with windows only. You don’t really need to install it. It is just a matter of unzipping the archive and execute the program inside.
Run the program. Move the map to the location and level of zoom you want. For a first time, i suggest you choose a small area with significant hills or mountain. Do not choose a complete region or country for your first try. The files will be probably too big to complete the process. There are some workarounds for that, but anticipate some additional work. Once at the correct location , i suggest you define it as “home location” to find it more easily next time. (type “set-home” in the console at the bottom)
Today I have decided to work on this lovely part of France which is dear to my heart:

By defaults, the working zone is you current window size.
You can “lock” the working zone, by using the menu Map/Set Geometry Bounds and Map/Set Printing Bounds . This way, the working zone will not be affected even if the window is resized. This is also convenient, if you want to have a square piece of map.
Now, we are facing a tricky part:
Maperitive is using the topographic data from USGS to get the elevation information.
Unfortunately, the USGS a restricted the automated access to these data and this part of maperitive is now broken.
There is a workaroung though:

  • Note the latitude longitude of the part of map you want to work with. Today it is 46.2°N4.6°E
  • I have to get the corresponding SRTM3 files . It is named according to the coordinate. In ma case, i have to find the file 46N004E.hgt.zip .
  • If your working zone covers several degrees of latitude/longitude , you may need several of these files.
  • To do so , you have to browse this site: https://dds.cr.usgs.gov/srtm/versio...
    Download the corresponding zip files.
    Unzip them and Copy the hgt files in the Subfolder of the Maperitive program named Maperitive\Cache\Rasters\SRTM3
    You can now go back in Maperitive.
  • Type CTRL+SHIFT+C
  • After a few seconds, you should see beautiful elevation contours.

In the Map menu, make sure to untick “Show Map Scale” and “Show Grid”.
In the “Map Sources” Tab , in the lower right corner, make sure to untick all map source except the contours. The map should switch to blank leaving only the elevation layers.
Go to the Menu “Tools / Export to SVG (Inkscape)”
Browse to the “output” subfolder of the Maperitive working directory. You should find a output.svg file. You can open it with your usual web browser, you should see your elevation lines.
Rename output.svg in something meaningful for you. in my case “DEMO-elevation.svg”.
No let’s go back in Maperitive.
Go to the Menu “Tools / Export to 3D”
Browse to the “output / Maperitive3D” subfolder of the Maperitive working directory. You should find a Maperitive3D.dae file. It is a “Collada” file. I can not use it directly in Fusion, so let’s convert it.

Open your web browser to : http://www.greentoken.de/onlineconv...
Upload the DAE file and request a STL conversion.

Download the converted STL file and rename it in something meaningful for you. in my case “DEMO-3DModel.stl”.
Let’s go back to Maperitive.
In the “Map Sources” Tab , in the lower right corner, make sure to untick all map source. the screen should now be blank.
Type CTRL+SHIFT+D .
New vector maps data are downloaded and displayed.

Now, let’s go in the “Rules” subdirectory of the Maperitive Directory. download and copy the three mrules files attached to this thingiverse "thing".

Then go back to Maperitive.
In the command line at the bottom type the following:
use-ruleset location=Rules/Custom-Waterways-only.mrules
and then:
apply-ruleset

You should get a different render of the map: only blue line for rivers, green line for paved roads and red lines for smaller walkways.
Next time , you will not need to create the file and type the command. Simply go to menu Map / Switch to Rules / Custom-Waterways-only.mrules
If you are nerd enough you can tweak the mrules file to adapt the rendering to your needs.

Once again, we will export the map to svg:
Go to the Menu “Tools / Export to SVG (Inkscape)”
Browse to the “output” subfolder of the Maperitive working directory. You should find a output.svg file. You can open it with your usual web browser, you should see your elevation lines.
Rename output.svg in something meaningful for you. in my case “DEMO-Waterways.svg”.
Let’s repeat these steps for other types of informations:

Apply the rule set Custom-Named-Road-only.mrules , export as svg and save it with a proper name.

Then again for “Custom-Non-Named-Road.mrules”

This step is now complete. You can close Maperitive.
You should have now: one stl file and four svg files.

Step 2: Prepare the 3D model in Fusion360.

First you need to have Fusion 360 on your computer. I assume you already have some knowledge of it.
If you don’t have it already, i am afraid it will be quite a big step to start with this project. There are a ton of tutorial on Youtube. Please follow some of them and get back once you will be more familiar with Fusion.
I am not myself an advanced user. Many things here can be improved and i hope you will be able to help me to be more efficient. Feel free to comment.
This being said, let’s run Fusion360.
Open a new project,
Keep in mind that you should save frequently your work. Fusion360 will be under significant CPU load and i have met several crashes.
Create a new component (and activate it)
Click the insert button drop-down menu ; select insert mesh, and insert the stl file created earlier.
You should now see our 3D surface. Unfortunately, this is quite heavy , so i’d like to reduce the number of triangles in the mesh:
Right click on the top level of the tree on the left and select “do not capture design history”.
In the tree select the meshbody you have inserted and swith to the “Mesh” environment.
Then use the remesh function. I kept the default settings.

I am now going back to “model” environment. I right click on the mesh (in the tree) and use the Mesh-to-Brep function.
The newly created BRep body should be now highlighted.
Right click on the top level of the tree on the left and select “Capture design history”.
Now, create a sketch on the horizontal plane. Draw a rectangle with dimensions identical to the projection on the horizontal plane of your piece of 3D map.
Offset this rectangle to create a second rectangle smaller by a very small amount (let’s say 1mm) than the first one.
Extrude the smaller rectangle with enough length to have it higher than the highest mountain of your 3D map.

Now, we will cut the box in 2 parts with the 3D surface.
Use the Split body command (in the modifydrop down menu) and select the box as the body to split and the 3D surface as the cutting tool.
Make sure to select the complete 3D body as cutting tool (by clicking it in the tree on the left) . If you click directly on the object, you will select only one triangle.
After a few dozens of seconds, you should get 2 bodies intead of one.
You can now remove the upper part and hide the 3D plane that are not needed anymore.
We have now our solid ready:

It’s time to scale the model down to our printbed size. Using the “inspect” tool i measure the longer side of our model. in my case it is 6794mm wide (yes!). I want to downsize it to 250mm , so it is a scale factor of : 0,0367971.
Using the modify / scale tool, i apply this scale uniformly to the model.

I use the same tool again to scale the elevation only with a factor 2. This will increase the 3D effect of the map.

Finally I add a small pyramid, seperated from the main model but to be printed all together at the same time. This pyramid will be important for the final step.

This is it, we are now ready to 3D print.
Go to Make / 3D Print and export the STL file to your favorite slicer.
When the print is complete: Do not remove it from the bed. If you have a glass or mirror bed held by clips, make sure to note touch anything.

After printing, i suggest you to use a primer to have a smoother surface.
I use myself the Optimus primer from filament-abs.fr :https://www.filament-abs.fr/produit/produit-de-lissage-optimus/

Step 3: Prepare the Gcode for drawing

In the model environment, let’s create a construction plane parallel to the ground plane. I offset it by a few centimers as i want it to be above the highest hill of my model.

Now, This new plane being selected, click import / Import SVG file and select one of the svg file created at step 1. In my case, i will chose the simplest one (the waterways) to make it easier for fusion.

Now, this is the step that is the most difficult for me at this stage. I don’t know how to automate that.
You have to align the svg file and the 3D model. You need to adjust both the position and the scale. I don’t know how do it except by repeating trials and mistakes.
After finalizing the svg positioning a new sketch is created according to the svg drawing.

it is now time to let the magic happens, Let’s switch to the CAM environment.
In the CAM, click “New Setup”.
In the first tab, configure as shown on this screenshot.
Make sure to configure the coordinate system as the printer works. and the origin should be the top of the pyramid.

In the second tab, select the stock as “from solid” and select both bodies (the 3D model and the pyramid).

The third tab can be left unchanged. You can click OK.

Now, in the “3D” dropdown menu, Select “Project” in order to create the toolpath for our pen.
First, let’s select our tool. I choose a random spot drill of small size. But if I have time to loose some day, i will create a tool that will reflect more accurately our pen holder.
Disable coolant.
Change the feed speed to 1000mm/min.

That’s it for the first tab.

In the second tab, we are going to select all the curves we want to draw. Here There is a tip:
When you will click on curve, only a small segment of the curve will be highlighted. You need to click a second time and then to move the mouse along the curve to select it entirely. Then click on the green “+” to confirm the selection.
You can see a screencast of this operation here: https://screencast.autodesk.com/Embed/Timeline/515d49ab-d913-4889-bc8d-4571ff9f8ba4

In the third tab, we define the various reference height in our project.
Top height defines the highest point of the model.
Retract height defines by how mm we will offset the pen when we don’t want to draw.
Clearance height defines the level for fast move.
The values below are not optimized , but whatever, At this stage i am not looking at reducing my machine time.

In the last tab, You can leave everything unchanged but the last item: The entry point chould be your origin (the top of the pyramid).

You can now enjoy a simulation: Press simulate and watch your pen following the surface of your terrain:

It is now time to generate the Gcode corresponding to that movement of the pen.
Here I have to give huge credits to Tech2C. He inspires this project with his video where he converts his Hypercube printer into a plotter.

Let’s download his Hypercube.cps on thingiverse: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2459624/#files
And put in on the Autodesk cloud following this tutorial: https://knowledge.autodesk.com/support/fusion-360/learn-explore/caas/sfdcarticles/sfdcarticles/How-to-install-a-cloud-post-in-Fusion-360.html

Once it is done, let’s go back in Fusion360; and click the postprocessor button.
Press Setup and select “Cloud Posts”.
Then in the Post configuration select Hypercube.cps,
Finally select the folder in which you want to output the gcode and choose a proper name (and a fancy text to be shown on the printer LCD if you wish).

After pressing print, you will get your Gcode file:

You can preview the result with a gcode simulator such as: https://nraynaud.github.io/webgcode/
(Do not try a gcode simulator dedicated to 3D printer such as gcode.ws or the one in octopi. They won’t work).

Put the gcode on your Sdcard and load it on the printer.
Install a permanent pen in the pen holder.
Gently move manually the axis in order to have the tip of the pen on the top of the pyramid.
the tip of the pen has to be perfectly aligned (on X and Y axis) with the tip of the pyramid.
Regarding Z axis, the pen tip should apply a very gentle pressure. Just as much pressure as you would apply manually to draw with this pen.
Start the print . And pray. You should get the expected result.
If you wish to play with my files, they are available here:
The fusion project is available here: http://a360.co/2x0uyrw

Step 4 : Enjoy your work

Have a beer and a good sleep. And tommorrow, come back and let me know your comments.

description.text:
This is a small camera holder for robots described in: http://duckietown.org/

It is a small plastic part, that holds the fisheye camera at a certain angle in front of the duckiebot. Since the original part was hard to find, and the only stores that had it asked for expensive shipping, so I decided to make a replacement with my 3d printer. When assembled, it will hold the camera at the exact angle and position as the original plastic piece does.

I am also including the sketchup drawings, so if anyone needs to make a modification they can.

Assembly Instructions:

  • Pop 2 M3 plastic bolts to the bottom part of the holder. The hex shaped openings could print a little irregular, but if you use back of a screwdriver the M3 bolts will pop in.

  • Push 4 M2 metal screws (I salvaged mine from a used lenovo laptop) in the back of the holder. I used a little ABS cement to secure them in place.

  • Attach the ribbon to the camera, and pass the ribbon from the opening in the part. Then put the camera and screw it in.

  • Attach the camera holder to the duckiebot, notice that a thin screwdriver has access from the bottom holes of the robot, as shown in last picture. Pull the camera to the most fron position on the holes of the chasis.

description.text:
Dondolo X Carriage Kit to fit on "Acrylic Geeetech I3 Pro B with metal kit parts"

The purpose of this design is to install the "Dondolo" on the Geeetech I3 Pro B without losing the z-stroke, otherwise the stepper motor and the servo would hit the top of the chassis. Here is the reason for the 13mm spacer. The fan duct has been redesigned to fit the new configuration. Another necessary change was to move the belt holder higher than the original "Dondolo" carriage.

01/12/2017
The project has finally been completed!

First of all a big thanks to Alberto (MagoKimbra) for debugging his MK4Duo firmware which now works perfectly with the "GT2560" board.

And of course Gianni Franci for the wonderful concept.

You can configure your firmware on MagoKimbra's page: http://www.marlinkimbra.it/

The firmware to be configured is this: "MK4duo - Firmware configurator tool (Rev 4.3.2x) - Firmware Version 4.3.29 dev"

Configure everything through the web interface, at the end check the assignment of the servo pin, that for the GT2560 Rev A+ must be Pin11 (maybe 13 for the Rev A)

Edit the file "7.h" located in this folder: \MK4duo\src\ boards\
as shown below

// ### SERVO
// #define SERVO0_PIN 32

define SERVO0_PIN 11

If you want to use the original Marlin firmware, you have to make the changes you find in the documentation of Gianni Franci "DONDOLO_v1_firmware_setup_guide.pdf" and then, in "Configuration.h", put false in "#define DISABLE_INACTIVE_EXTRUDER"
as shown below

// Disables axis when it's not being used.

define DISABLE_X false

define DISABLE_Y false

define DISABLE_Z false

define DISABLE_E false // For all extruders

define DISABLE_INACTIVE_EXTRUDER false // disable only inactive extruders and keep active extruder enabled

Remember, however, that the original marlin does not allow the Z offset between the two nozzles.

description.text:
This is a foam dart shell compatible with Dart Zone's Dartstorm motorized flywheel belt blaster. There are two primary designs for this item:

-- "Interlocking Foam Dart Belt Shell.stl" - These shells, while similar to the shells that come packaged with the Dart Zone Dartstorm blaster, are distinct in that they can be connected together to form a belt without the need for pins. These shells can be seen in the attached pictures printed with black PETG filament. The stl file for this design with supports has a flat base that takes some material away from the top brim and the outside tube wall. This makes for much easier/cleaner/stable prints, and it does not seem to affect performance cycling through the Dartstorm blaster.

-- "Foam Dart Belt Shell.stl" - This item is similar to the shells that come packaged with the Dart Zone Dartstorm blaster. You will need some variety of pin to lock the shells together to form a belt. I have found that pointed toothpick ends cut and crimped into place work well as an inexpensive and ubiquitous alternative to the metal pins that come with the stock Dart Zone shells.

STL files with supports are included for both designs.

You should make the parts really solid, since it's dealing with serious force. I was printing with 0.8mm nozzle and had 4 layers around the models. I printed my part with PLA 0.2mm layer height.

For constructing this you'll need to print:

  • 2 x hooks (Requires support)
  • 2 x rolls
  • 1 x screw
  • 1 x body
  • 1 x swivel

Also you need to acquire:

  • about 1m of high strength cord (I used paracord)
  • 2 x 6x40mm bolts

I simulated the hooks at Fusion 360 and it seems to behave ok with 700N force.
-> https://www.instagram.com/p/BY-taC_gFJz/?hl=en&taken-by=heikkimus
One more time, make it very very very sturdy and solid, otherwise it will explode on your eyes.

Fusion 360-files can be found from https://gallery.autodesk.com/fusion360/projects/3d-printed-bow-press-for-compound-bow?popupSNS=true

title: Modified Cobra Cooler (w/ extra clearance)(for Wanhao Duplicator i3v.2 / v.2.1)

description.text:
Remix of the Cobra Cooler Fan Shroud by tahustvedt.

I modified the shape of the cooler to give an extra 2.5mm of clearance from the bed. For some reason, the stock design always touches the bed when the nozzle is homed to Z. I also removed the rear screw hole for easier removal/installation of the fan shroud.

Prints fine with PLA, but I recommend PETG/PC for long-term use.

Requires:
1x 12V 50x50x15 mm blower fan
1x M4x45 mm screw for mounting the duct to the printer (for v2.1)
1x M4x20 mm screw for mounting the blower to the duct
1x printed v2.1 adaptor (by emila)(for v2.1 machines)
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1703941

Full credits to tahustvedt who made this shroud. IMHO, the cobra cooler has the perfect balance between simplicity and cooling ability. It has become my mainstay cooler for 2 years now.
